{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657486"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20493"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20493"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13366"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76240"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11782"},{"type":"tags","id":"12421"},{"type":"tags","id":"12422"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the emergency department with severe chest pain. Investigations confirm he has suffered a myocardial infarction. The patient undergoes appropriate treatment and is discharged after five days. During follow-up, his cardiologist explains that some of his heart tissue has been permanently damaged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the repair process that occurs in the damaged myocardium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Replacement of damaged tissue with connective tissue","Conversion of fibroblasts into functional cardiac myocytes","Complete regeneration of cardiac myocytes","Recruitment of circulating myocyte precursors","Proliferation of surviving cardiac stem cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereplacement of damaged tissue with connective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. When cardiac myocytes die following a myocardial infarction, they have minimal capacity for regeneration. Instead, the repair process involves the formation of a collagenous scar. This represents repair by connective tissue deposition, which is a patching mechanism rather than true restoration of the original tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete regeneration of cardiac myocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - Adult cardiac myocytes have extremely limited capacity for division and regeneration. The heart cannot fully regenerate after significant damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of fibroblasts into functional cardiac myocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - While this is an area of research interest, natural transdifferentiation of fibroblasts into functional cardiac myocytes does not occur to any significant extent during normal repair.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProliferation of surviving cardiac stem cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Although there is some evidence for cardiac stem cells, their contribution to repair after myocardial infarction is minimal and insufficient for functional recovery.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecruitment of circulating myocyte precursors\u003C/strong\u003E - There is limited evidence that circulating stem cells contribute significantly to cardiac repair after infarction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScar formation is not limited to the skin but occurs in any tissue where parenchymal cells with limited regenerative capacity are damaged, including the heart, brain, and kidneys. The scar provides structural integrity but lacks the functional properties of the original tissue, which can lead to impaired organ function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tissue repair occurs by regeneration when possible, but when regeneration is insufficient, repair occurs by connective tissue deposition (scarring).","Scar formation is a patching response rather than a true restoration of original tissue architecture and function.","Scarring can occur in any tissue where parenchymal cells are replaced by collagen, not just in the skin."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 105."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76240"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20493"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76240"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T19:30:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T16:06:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13366"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92875"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","upda